## Bandwidth and Cutoff
Since the model in this paper is RDD, the cutoff and bandwidth needs to be defined. Firms with a score of 75 and above will be subsidized, making score 75 the sharp cutoff. 

To analyze the effectiveness of the program in supporting R&D, the treatment and comparison groups should be selected to maintain the similarity between the two groups [@Gertler]. Since this dataset contains only 357 observations and was skewed towards the right of the cutoff, three bandwidth values were selected to maintain statistical power of the model, namely, the full sample, wide-window bandwidth (which contains 50% of the sample in each side of the cutoff) and the narrow-window bandwidth (which contains 35% of the sample in each side of the cutoff). 

This paper tests difference between the control and treatment groups for both the low and high capital firms by examining their pre-program assets, pre-program capital and pre-program sales. As shown in (Table \@ref(Tab:Table1)) low capital firms, the control and treatment groups do no show statistically mean difference with the narrow window bandwidth (score 62-79), which suggest that the control and treatment groups for narrow window bandwidth do not differ significantly in pre-program assets, pre-program capital and pre-program sales. The paper considers the two groups similar in nature. However, the treatment and control groups for the full window showed significant difference in sales and capital, and the treatment and control groups for the wide window (score 34-81) showed significant difference in sales and assets. Therefore, comparing these groups may undermine the internal validity of the RDD model. 

As shown in (Table \@ref(Tab:Table2)) low capital firms, the control and treatment groups do no show statistically mean difference with the narrow window bandwidth (score 61-79),  and the wide window (score 52 -80), which suggest that the control and treatment groups do not differ significantly in pre-program assets, pre-program capital and pre-program sales. The paper considers the two groups similar in nature. However, the treatment and control groups for the full window showed significant difference in sales, assets and capital. Therefore, comparing these groups may undermine the internal validity of the RDD model.

Based on the analysis above, the paper will analyze the high capital and low capital firms in their narrow window to examine the effectiveness of the program. 


```{r,include = FALSE, echo = FALSE}
# Defining high capital and low capital groups
fullWindowSmallCompanyData <- data %>%
                  mutate(smallmM = ifelse(K< medianK, 1, 0),
                         largemM = ifelse(K>= medianK, 1, 0)) %>%
                  filter(smallmM == 1) %>%
                  mutate(treatsmallM = (treat * smallmM),
                         treatlargeM = (treat * largemM),
                         ssmallM = (s * smallmM),
                         slargeM = (s * largemM),
                         streatsmallM = (s * treat * smallmM),
                         streatlargelM = (s * treat * largemM))%>%
              select(c("treat", "snotreat", "streat", "INVSALES", "INVTSALES", "INVINTSALES", "score", "SALES", "K", "ASSETS"))


fullWindowLargeCompanyData <- data %>%
                  mutate(smallFlag = ifelse(K< medianK, 1, 0),
                         largemM = ifelse(K>= medianK, 1, 0)) %>%
                  filter(smallFlag == 0) %>%
              select(c("treat", "snotreat", "streat", "INVSALES", "INVTSALES", "INVINTSALES", "score", "SALES", "K", "ASSETS"))

```


```{r fig.cap="Pre-Assignment Mean Difference between Untreated and Treated Low Capital Firms ",echo = FALSE}
# conduct the t test for Low Capital companies 
wideWindowLeftData <- fullWindowSmallCompanyData %>%
                  filter(score > 34 & score < 75)
wideWindowRightData <- fullWindowSmallCompanyData %>%
                  filter(score >= 75 & score < 81)


narrowWindowLeftData <- fullWindowSmallCompanyData %>%
                  filter(score > 62 & score < 75)
narrowWindowRightData <- fullWindowSmallCompanyData %>%
                  filter(score >= 75 & score < 79)

fullWindowLeftData <- fullWindowSmallCompanyData %>%
                  filter(score < 75)
fullWindowRightData <- fullWindowSmallCompanyData %>%
                  filter(score >= 75)
  
t1 <- t.test(fullWindowLeftData$SALES, fullWindowRightData$SALES)
t2 <- t.test(fullWindowLeftData$K, fullWindowRightData$K)
t3 <- t.test(fullWindowLeftData$ASSETS, fullWindowRightData$ASSETS)
t4 <- t.test(wideWindowLeftData$SALES, wideWindowRightData$SALES)
t5 <- t.test(wideWindowLeftData$K, wideWindowRightData$K)
t6 <- t.test(wideWindowLeftData$ASSETS, wideWindowRightData$ASSETS)
t7 <- t.test(narrowWindowLeftData$SALES, narrowWindowRightData$SALES)
t8 <- t.test(narrowWindowLeftData$K, narrowWindowRightData$K)
t9 <- t.test(narrowWindowLeftData$ASSETS, narrowWindowRightData$ASSETS)

name <- c("Sales", "Capital", "Assets", "Sales", "Capital", "Assets", "Sales", "Capital", "Assets")
map_df(list(t1, t2, t3, t4, t5, t6, t7, t8, t9), tidy) %>%
  cbind(name) %>%
  select(c("name", "estimate", "statistic", "p.value", "conf.low", "conf.high", "method")) %>%
  rename( `Mean-Difference` = estimate,
          `P-value` = p.value,
          `95% CI Low` = conf.low,
          `95% CI High` = conf.high,
          `Variabel` = name,
          Method = method) %>% 
  kableExtra::kable(caption="Pre-Assignment Mean Difference between Untreated and Treated Low Capital Firms",align = "cccccc") %>%
  pack_rows("Full Window", 1,3) %>%
  pack_rows("Wide Window", 4,6) %>%
  pack_rows("Narrow Window", 7,9) %>%
  kable_styling(latex_options = "hold_position") 
```

