# Model 

## Regression Discoutinuity Design 

To test the effectiveness of the Program in boosting firms' R&D investment, the most ideal way is to randomly select two groups of companies with the same qualities and provide funding to one of the group. However, this can be difficult to perform in real life. This paper, same as the Bronzini and Iachini paper, instead chooses the quasi-experiment RDD method to examine the program impact given that the firms are selected for treatment of receiving subsidies based on whether their score falls above or below 75. 

The model can be used in this scenario as it satisfies the assumptions of RDD raised by Gertler [@Gertler]. Firstly, the scores of the firms are continuous and the cutoff (score = 75) is clearly defined. Secondly, firms cannot freely manipulate their score since the score is given by an independent panel of experts. We have found that firms with score of 74 are apparently low in density, but this is not considered to invalidate the design. The drop in density of firms with score 74 is likely due to the experts avoiding appeals against the decisions,and this is less likely caused by firms manipulating the score. Lastly, section 2.4 has shown that the treatment and comparison units selected are of sufficient similarities for the RDD method. This paper do recognize that due to the limitation in sample size and the availability of the outcome variable, the model may face some limitations. This will be discussed in detail in Discussion section. Overall, this paper believes that RDD is the ideal model to conduct this research.



## Model Construction {#model}
Taking all of the above into consideration, the paper proposes the following model to evaluate the impact the program has on firms' R&D investment two years from the program start date:

$$Y_{i} = \alpha + \beta T_{i} + (1-T_{i})f(S_{i}) + T_{i}f'(S_{i}) +\epsilon_{i}$$

where 

* $Y_{i}$ is the R&D investment outcome for firm $i$, which is represented by variables (1) Total investment/pre-program sales, (2) Tangible investment/pre-program sales, (3) Intangible investment/pre-program sales. 

* $T_{i}$ represents whether firm $i$ has been subsidized or not. T_{i} = 1 if firm $i$ is subsidized (score_{i} > = 75) and T_{i} = 0 if firm $i$ is not subsidized (score_{i} t < 75). And its coefficient $\beta_{0}$ is the estimate of the program's impact on firms R&D investment when they receive the subsidies. 

* $S_{i}$ is Score_{i} - 75, and the functions $f(S_{i})$ and $f'(S_{i})$ are allowed to be different on the opposite side of the cutoff to allow for heterogeneity of the function in the left and right side of the cutoff. 

* $\epsilon_{i}$ is the random error of the function. 

Bronzini and Iachini estimate up to a third-order polynomial model in their paper and the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) value for the models suggested a preference for more simple models. Since the method used in this paper is the same as that in the Bronzini and Iachini's paper, the paper uses the first order polynomial for the model construct. 

As discussed in the Data section, these outcome variables are continuous, therefore, this paper will use the linear regression model for the analysis. This paper will use the model to examine the high capital group and the low capital group sepeately. 


# Results

## Low Capital Group 

For firms with low capital, the coefficients for the treatment variable T_{i} are shown in the "subsidized" row in (Table \@ref(Tab:Table4)). The $\beta_{0}$ coefficient for T_{i} is significant in the total investment/pre-program sales model and the intangible investment/pre-program sales model but not on the tangible investment/pre-program sales model at a 95% confidence interval. Subsidizing a firm through the program will lead to a 0.101 increase in the firm's total investment/pre-program sales and a increase of 0.068 in the firm's intangible investment/pre-program sales. (Figure \@ref(fig:fig05)) shows the program's influence to firms in the low capital groups graphically. 


```{r, include = FALSE, echo = FALSE}

fullSmallINVSALES <- lm(INVSALES ~ treat  + snotreat + streat, 
                   data = fullWindowSmallCompanyData)
fullSmallINVTSALES <- lm(INVTSALES ~ treat  + snotreat + streat, 
                   data = fullWindowSmallCompanyData)
fullSmallINVINTSALES <- lm(INVINTSALES ~ treat  + snotreat + streat, 
                   data = fullWindowSmallCompanyData)

# Narrow window for the small size companies
wideWindowSmallData <- fullWindowSmallCompanyData %>%
                  filter(score > 34 & score < 81) 

wideSmallINVSALES <- lm(INVSALES ~ treat  + snotreat + streat, 
                   data = wideWindowSmallData)
wideSmallINVTSALES <- lm(INVTSALES ~ treat  + snotreat + streat, 
                   data = wideWindowSmallData)
wideSmallINVINTSALES <- lm(INVINTSALES ~ treat  + snotreat + streat, 
                   data = wideWindowSmallData)

# Narrow window for the small size companies
narrowWindowSmallData <- fullWindowSmallCompanyData %>%
                  filter(score > 62 & score < 79)

narrowSmallINVSALES <- lm(INVSALES ~ treat  + snotreat + streat, 
                   data = narrowWindowSmallData)
narrowSmallINVTSALES <- lm(INVTSALES ~ treat  + snotreat + streat, 
                   data = narrowWindowSmallData)
narrowSmallINVINTSALES <- lm(INVINTSALES ~ treat  + snotreat + streat, 
                   data = narrowWindowSmallData)
```

```{r, Table3, fig.cap="Effect of the Program on Investment--Low Capital Firms ", echo = FALSE, message = FALSE, warning=FALSE}
modelsummary(list("Total Investment" = narrowSmallINVSALES, "Tangible Investment" = narrowSmallINVTSALES,"Intangible Investment" =  narrowSmallINVINTSALES),
             statistic = "{std.error} ({p.value})",
             stars =TRUE,
             coef_map = c("(Intercept)" = "Constant", "treat" = "Founded"),
             exponentiate = TRUE,
             title = "Effect of the Program on Investment--Low Capital Firms",
             gof_omit = "BIC") %>% 
  add_footnote(c("Odds Ratio in First Row. Standard Error of Log of Odds in Second Row. P-value in Parentheses","Addjusted for pre-program sales. Therefore, the variables are Total Investment/pre-program sales, Tangible Investment/pre-program sales, Intangible Investment/pre-program sales"), notation = "number") %>% 
  kable_styling(latex_options = "hold_position")
```


```{r, include=FALSE}
